  "text": "The Kubernetes controller work queue with rate limiting is a sophisticated system implemented in the client-go package at staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/util/workqueue/. The implementation consists of several layered interfaces and implementations:\n\n## Core Interface Hierarchy\n\nThe foundation is the TypedInterface (queue.go:29-37) which defines the basic queue operations: Add(item), Get(), Done(item), Len(), and ShutDown(). This is implemented by the Typed[T] struct in queue.go (lines 188-212).\n\n## Delaying Queue\n\nThe TypedDelayingInterface (delaying_queue.go:36-40) extends TypedInterface with AddAfter(item, duration) capability, allowing items to be requeued with delays. The delayingType[T] struct (delaying_queue.go:153-172) wraps a basic queue and manages a priority queue of delayed items via waitingLoop().\n\n## Rate Limiting Layer\n\nThe TypedRateLimitingInterface (rate_limiting_queue.go:27-40) further extends TypedDelayingInterface with AddRateLimited(item) and Forget(item) methods. It is implemented by rateLimitingType[T] (rate_limiting_queue.go:130-147), which wraps a TypedDelayingInterface and a TypedRateLimiter.\n\n## Rate Limiter Implementations\n\nThe core rate limiter interface TypedRateLimiter[T] (default_rate_limiters.go:30-38) defines When(item), Forget(item), and NumRequeues(item) methods. Key implementations include:\n\n1. **TypedItemExponentialFailureRateLimiter** (default_rate_limiters.go:84-149): Implements exponential backoff using formula baseDelay*2^<num-failures>. Tracks failure counts per item and caps delays at maxDelay.\n\n2. **TypedBucketRateLimiter** (default_rate_limiters.go:62-77): Adapts golang.org/x/time/rate's token bucket algorithm to the workqueue API. Provides a simple global QPS limit regardless of item count.\n\n3. **TypedMaxOfRateLimiter** (default_rate_limiters.go:218-259): Composes multiple limiters and returns the most restrictive delay. Commonly used with NewTypedMaxOfRateLimiter combining ItemExponential and BucketRateLimiter for both per-item and overall rate control.\n\n## Queue Construction Pattern\n\nQueues are typically created with NewTypedRateLimitingQueue() which chains the layers: base queue → delaying queue → rate limiting queue. The DefaultTypedControllerRateLimiter() (default_rate_limiters.go:50-56) creates a MaxOfRateLimiter combining exponential backoff (5ms base, 1000s max) with token bucket (10 QPS, 100 burst).\n\n## Controller Reconcile Loop\n\nThe sample-controller/controller.go demonstrates the canonical pattern (lines 193-236):\n\n1. **runWorker()** continuously calls processNextWorkItem in a loop\n2. **processNextWorkItem()** executes: Get() to retrieve an item, defer Done() to mark completion\n3. On success: call Forget(item) to stop retrying\n4. On transient error: call AddRateLimited(item) to requeue with exponential backoff\n\nThe key methods are:\n- **Add(item)** in queue.go:235-259: Marks item as dirty, moves from processing to queue if needed\n- **Get()** in queue.go:273-292: Pops from queue, adds to processing set, waits if empty\n- **Done(item)** in queue.go:297-310: Removes from processing, re-adds to queue if marked dirty during processing\n- **AddRateLimited(item)** in rate_limiting_queue.go:137-139: Calls AddAfter with duration from rateLimiter.When()\n- **Forget(item)** in rate_limiting_queue.go:145-147: Clears failure tracking from the rate limiter\n\nThis design ensures controllers process items sequentially without hot-looping on failures, with configurable per-item exponential backoff and global QPS throttling. The pattern is used throughout kubernetes/kubernetes controllers (job_controller, namespace_controller, replicaset, endpointslice, service controllers, etc.)."
}
